{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527852"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:34:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:34:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14239"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14239"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.11,0.03,0.2,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55602"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6926"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41142"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"325"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18213"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55602"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of sudden onset left-sided abdominal pain which started after a coughing fit. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation, for which she takes warfarin. She was recently prescribed a course of roxithromycin for a chest infection. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in obvious pain. Her pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 115/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a tender left-sided abdominal wall swelling. Investigations reveal a haemoglobin of 98 g/L (119-160) and INR of 7.0 (2.0-3.5). A CT scan is performed (Images 1- 2). A four-factor prothrombin complex concentrate is administered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continued observation","Abdominal wall binder","Application of ice packs","Incision and drainage","Angioembolisation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a rectus sheath haematoma, likely caused by coughing while on anticoagulation therapy. The CT scan shows a left-sided rectus sheath haematoma with active extravasation from the left inferior epigastric artery. Reversal of the anticoagulant (in this case with a prothrombin complex) will be the quickest management and will often be all that is required. However in this case, given the evidence of ongoing bleeding, anaemia and borderline observations, more aggressive management is warranted. Reduction of INR will additionally be required to allow safe arterial access for the radiological procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngioembolisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management in this case. It allows for targeted control of the bleeding vessel without the need for open surgery. The procedure typically involves accessing the arterial system via the femoral artery and embolising the left inferior epigastric artery using materials such as gelfoam.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinued observation\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for a stable, non-expanding haematoma without evidence of ongoing bleeding. However, this patient has active extravasation on imaging and a dropping haemoglobin, indicating that observation alone is insufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal wall binder\u003C/strong\u003E can provide compression and may help limit expansion of a haematoma. While it might be used as an adjunct therapy, it\u0027s not sufficient as the primary management for active bleeding in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplication of ice packs\u003C/strong\u003E can help with pain relief and may slightly reduce local blood flow. However, like the abdominal binder, this is an adjunctive measure and not adequate to address the active bleeding seen on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for a rectus sheath haematoma. This procedure could potentially worsen bleeding and introduce infection. Rectus sheath haematomas are typically managed conservatively or with minimally invasive techniques like angioembolisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of rectus sheath haematomas depends on the severity and stability of the patient. Most cases can be managed conservatively with reversal of anticoagulation, pain control, and supportive care. However, in cases of active bleeding, especially in anticoagulated patients, more aggressive measures like angioembolisation are warranted. Surgery is rarely needed and typically reserved for cases with hemodynamic instability or failure of less invasive measures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of rectus sheath haematoma can be managed conservatively.","Angioembolisation is indicated for rectus sheath haematomas with active bleeding, especially in anticoagulated patients.","Rectus sheath haematomas can be caused by coughing in anticoagulated patients."],"references":["Hatjipetrou A, Anyfantakis D, Kastanakis M. Rectus sheath hematoma: A review of the literature. Int J Surg 2015;13:267-71. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25529279/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41142"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14239"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21039"},{"type":"media","id":"21040"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21039"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nRWQqzE1PLAZReuBEvyuO4siBTDbV5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nRWQqzE1PLAZReuBEvyuO4siBTDbV5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":719,"height":592}},{"type":"media","id":"21040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21040"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qEwx29fRdr3zwM4qXQR0TzFoe0V6ND.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qEwx29fRdr3zwM4qXQR0TzFoe0V6ND.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":526,"height":786}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41142"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-16T22:36:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T22:36:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6926"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55602"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gr